It is said that wit, more than strength, is the friend of the thirsty Crow. This was on the river bank.

At dusk by a farmhouse stoop, Caw the crow paused beside a chipped pitcher. The water inside, only 4 centimeters deep, sent up a thin reflection of the sky. She was dry-throated and desperate, and so she did what every clever crow knows to do: she gathered 11 acorns from the gravel along the path and dropped them in, one after another. Each acorn shouldered the water up by 2 centimeters, and she kept count.

