At dusk on a flat plain, the silhouettes of 4 bulls stood widely scattered, each carrying the same well-known strength 4. Roar the lion, of strength 6, watched the long shadows lean across the grass without complaint. The lion could meet any one of those silhouettes alone; the herd's combined strength of 16, however, would simply trample him. The bulls themselves shifted with growing alarm at every distant snap of grass. All that remained was the boolean: did the lion truly need them divided to win?

