Strength shared is strength multiplied — a truth the Lion knew well, and worked patiently to undo.

In a wide clearing rimmed by tall grass, 3 bulls stood at suspicious distances, each of strength 11. Roar the lion crossed the clearing without complaint, knowing his own strength to be 15. Single-handedly against a single bull, the lion held the upper paw; but if the herd closed ranks the combined strength of 33 would have made short work of him. The lion sat in the long shadow at the edge and considered: did victory depend strictly on keeping them apart?

Question: whether Roar can defeat each bull alone (lion-strength > bull-strength) yet would lose against the herd combined (lion-strength < combined-strength)?
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Let me work that out.

{"tool_calls":[{"name":"eval","args":{"form":"(let [lion-strength 15 bulls 3 bull-strength 11 combined-strength (* bulls bull-strength)] (and (> lion-strength bull-strength) (< lion-strength combined-strength)))"}}]}
<|end|>


