A young farmhand at the barn liked to come round at sunrise just to watch Jordan collect from the goose. The bird would settle, ruffle, and stand, leaving 3 golden eggs in the straw — never more, never fewer. Jordan would gather them grateful for every bite, smiling at the boy, and tuck them into a folded cloth. They kept up the routine for 11 days, and at the end the boy asked, eyes wide, just how many golden eggs the goose had given altogether.

Write a Clojure expression that computes how many eggs the goose laid in total over those 11 days.
