In a quiet courtyard Sable alighted wide-eyed with fear on the lip of a pitcher. Below, a sliver of water at 3 centimeters caught the last of the daylight — but their beak could only reach down to 18 centimeters, no further. A handful of smooth pebbles had been left near the doorway. They tested one: a single pebble pushed the water up by 3 centimeters. They began calculating how many it would take to bring the surface within reach.

