Beyond the kitchen garden's hedge, a tall trellis held up a pear tree's heaviest bough; from it the lowest golden pear swung 11 feet above the gravel path. Renard, dreaming of the next meal, took his measure with a single trial leap — a tidy 3 feet of upward bound, no more — and crouched to think. If each successive jump could be stacked on the gain of the last, how many would he need before his teeth could close on the pear's freckled skin?

Write a Clojure expression that computes the smallest number of leaps Renard needs to reach the fruit.
