On a wide hilltop pasture, 3 bulls had been grazing under the morning sun until petty rivalries pulled them apart. Thorn moved north of the spring, Boulder south, and the rest scattered to lower slopes. Mane the lion crouched among the scrub at the ridge untroubled by what others thought, taking the long view. She had learned, after one bruising failure, that a single bull on open ground took her a measured 1 day to bring down. With the herd now broken, Mane began to figure how many days the entire hunt would consume.

