Strength shared is strength multiplied — a truth the Lion knew well, and worked patiently to undo.

On a hilltop pasture, each of the 5 bulls had been weighed and trial-tested by the elder bulls in younger years, and each carried strength 10. Roar the lion, with strength 11, paced the ridge stepping deliberately. Alone, a bull would not stand against him; but pressed together, the herd's combined strength rose to 50, beyond anything one cat could meet. The bulls already paced apart, with growing alarm, no longer sure of one another. Whether the lion needed them divided to win was the only remaining question.

Write a Clojure expression that computes whether Roar can defeat each bull alone (lion-strength > bull-strength) yet would lose against the herd combined (lion-strength < combined-strength).
