A thirsty Crow had been searching all afternoon for water and was nearly ready to give up. It happened near the hilltop.

After hours of fruitless searching, Caw the crow glided down to a quiet garden, with a thirst that hurt to bear. There on a low wall stood a jar, and from above she could see a thin glimmer of water at the bottom — only 3 centimeters deep, and her beak could not reach unless the surface rose to 33 centimeters. A scattering of pebbles lay along the path. Each pebble, when dropped in, would push the water up by 3 centimeters. She began to count what she would need.

