The butcher had tied up 10 scraps of meat in a paper for Rex the dog to carry home, and the count had been said aloud, both of them nodding. On the footbridge over the river the paper sagged near the water; he saw a phantom dog with a richer parcel and, his eyes greedy with want, snapped — losing one scrap to the river. By evening, when the cook checked the parcel against the butcher's tally, the actual count fell short of the expected by exactly that single greedy moment.

